<HEADLINE>
<P>
FACES: A STRENUOUS WEEKEND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JANICE ARKATOV 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Can Brian Kerwin survive this weekend? It's still up in the air. 
</P>
<P>
By Sunday, the actor will have prepared two Thanksgiving dinners, finished 
memorizing his lines for the one-man "A Poster of the Cosmos" (for the Dec. 11 
"Because We Care" AIDS holiday benefit at the Taper), and put in eight 3 
1/2-hour performances of "Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?" at the Doolittle -- 
one on Tuesday, two on Wednesday, two on Friday, two on Saturday and one on 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
"After the first rehearsal, I just shook," says Kerwin, who's Nick to John 
Lithgow and Glenda Jackson's George and Martha. 
</P>
<P>
"For 3 1/2 hours, I'm either being berated or berating someone else. It's also 
a progressive situation of drunkenness. I walk in the door already loosened up 
and go downhill from there. By the second show, I really do feel hung-over, a 
little woozy. I went to a doctor once who said, 'Your body doesn't know you're 
faking up there.' It's true." 
</P>
<P>
"Cosmos" offers its own Angst. 
</P>
<P>
"Lanford Wilson wrote it to be done at AIDS benefits," Kerwin says of the 
25-minute monologue, a man's statement to the police after the death of his 
AIDS-stricken lover. Although he had been introduced to the piece some time ago 
by director David Galligan, the call to do it for this benefit came out of the 
blue -- and right in the middle of his Doolittle run. "I said, 'Sure, I've got 
all the time in the world.' " 
</P>
<P>
If he survives his theater commitments, the actor can relax and look forward to 
"Challenger," ABC's upcoming three-hour TV-movie about the 1986 shuttle 
explosion. 
</P>
<P>
"Of course, there was a lot of sadness," he says of his experience playing 
pilot Mike Smith. 
</P>
<P>
"But you can't play that tragedy. For them, there was no foreboding. Our movie 
ends with the countdown, the engines starting -- and the astronauts' faces 
beaming as they go into outer space." JANICE ARKATOV 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Brian Kerwin: "By the second show, I really do feel hung-over, a little 
woozy." ROBERT GABRIEL / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
