<HEADLINE>
<P>
FACES: SLAP-HAPPY KIND OF GUY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVID PECCHIA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Did you, actor Larry Romano, repeatedly slap the face of pop sensation Madonna 
last Oct. 28? 
</P>
<P>
Romano is guilty as charged, and this offense is documented in "Oh, Father," 
the Platinum One's newest video. He portrays Madonna's whiskey-breath boyfriend 
in the clip. 
</P>
<P>
"It took about 10 or 11 takes," says the 25-year-old actor, who was most 
recently seen in Sly Stallone's latest flop "Lock Up." 
</P>
<P>
"It took awhile," Romano says, his voice big with the cadence of the Bronx. "I 
didn't want to (really whack her), but she told me to, so I ended up doing it 
anyhow." 
</P>
<P>
Madonna had spotted Romano in the Stallone film, then again in Interview 
magazine and mentioned her interest to a mutual friend. When word got back to 
Romano that the Material Girl had expressed admiration, he jumped into his game 
plan. All-around player Romano, who is currently working on a screenplay that's 
been optioned, also composes the occasional tune. 
</P>
<P>
"Let me get in touch with her because I've got a song," Romano told the friend 
they shared. 
</P>
<P>
"So I sent the tape over there to her, and she said, 'Listen, you might be 
right for this video. Do you want to do it?' " A few meetings with her, and he 
was cast. 
</P>
<P>
Romano was required to time the face-slap with a cymbal hit, and being an 
ex-musician evidently helped him. 
</P>
<P>
"Good thing I was a drummer," he says, "it made it a little easier to hit her 
on the crash. You know what I'm saying?" DAVID PECCHIA 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Larry Romano, on musical timing of his big slap: "Good thing I was a 
drummer." BARBARA ALPER 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
