<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEEKEND TV; 
</P>
<P>
'COLUMBO' RETURNS AND SAMMY DAVIS LEADS SUNDAY'S 'HOLLYWOOD CHRISTMAS PARADE' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE WEINSTEIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Peter Falk, Sammy Davis Jr., Walter Cronkite and winners and losers from the 
1988 Summer Olympics in Seoul strut their stuff on the small screen as the long 
holiday weekend winds down. 
</P>
<P>
Falk returns, trench coat and all, tonight at 9 on ABC (Channels 7, 3, 10 and 
42) as America's favorite rumpled detective in the season premiere of 
"Columbo." Falk will reappear periodically this season in rotation with Burt 
Reynolds, Jaclyn Smith and Telly Savalas in the "ABC Saturday Mystery." 
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, local viewers can avoid the traffic snarls by staying home and 
watching the 58th annual "Hollywood Christmas Parade" at 6 p.m. on Channel 5. 
Sammy Davis Jr. is this year's grand marshal. Bob Eubanks and Leeza Gibbons 
will host the live telecast. 
</P>
<P>
Sunday night at 9, CBS (Channels 2 and 8) looks back at "Fifty Years of 
Television," with clips and highlights from the small screen's first half 
century. Walter Cronkite, Carl Reiner, Jane Seymour and Kermit the Frog serve 
as emcees for this stroll down memory lane. 
</P>
<P>
Also Sunday at 9 p.m., the Disney Channel offers a series of compelling 
memories from the last Summer Games in Bud Greenspan's documentary, "Seoul '88: 
16 Days of Glory." 
</P>
<P>
Greenspan's deft ability to capture the moving human stories behind the 
magnificent accomplishments of such athletes as Christa Rothenburger, Vladimir 
Salnikov, Louise Ritter and Calvin Smith put to shame the commercial-saturated 
and superficial live network Olympic coverage to which Americans are 
accustomed. 
</P>
<P>
Other weekend shows include: 
</P>
<P>
TODAY: "Youth &amp; the Issues" looks at the rights of crime victims, 7 a.m. 
(9). . . . 
