706 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BOB GREENE: WHAT'S IN A NAME -- AND A DECADE? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An editor for one of those trend-setting, Manhattan-based glossy women's 
magazines called with a question: 
</P>
<P>
What did I think would be a good name for the '90s? 
</P>
<P>
I thought I might have misunderstood. "The '90s haven't even started yet," I 
said. 
</P>
<P>
"We know that," she said. "But we are asking several people to come up with a 
name for it." 
</P>
<P>
"What kind of a name?" I said. 
</P>
<P>
"Anything you want to name it," she said. "Sort of like the 'Me Decade,' but 
for the '90s." 
</P>
<P>
"No one even has any idea what's going to happen in the '90s," I said. "Usually 
people wait until a decade is over -- or at least until it's been around for a 
few years -- to give it a name." 
</P>
<P>
"Yes, but we want to get this into our January, 1990 issue," she said. 
</P>
<P>
I began to understand. In this hurry-up world of intense media competition, no 
one wants to be last -- or even second -- to hit the airwaves or the public 
prints with a concept. Granted, no one has any idea what the '90s will be like, 
but if you wait until 1998 or 1999 to name the decade, you're going to be 
standing at the end of a very long line. 
</P>
<P>
Which brings us to the real point here: if you think of the '90s as a person, 
you've got to feel a little sorry for the poor guy. Born into a world he never 
made, he's facing disadvantages that the decades preceding him could not have 
even imagined. 
</P>
<P>
Most decades are allowed to be born, to feel their way around for a couple of 
years, to develop a personality, to mature and then to fade peacefully away. 
The '90s, though, are going to have to hit the ground running. As a matter of 
fact -- thinking again of the '90s as a person -- this poor baby has been 
forced to sprint full speed while he is still in the womb. I think it was 1987, 
maybe 1988, when magazines started heralding "the end of the '80s." The decade 
was over, or so we were told, even though the calendar indicated otherwise. 
</P>
<P>
Part of this was based on societal trends; the pundits had decided that greed 
and ruthless acquisitiveness, which they associated with the '80s, were going 
out of fashion -- a questionable assertion at best, but one from which the deep 
thinkers extrapolated the idea that not only was greed dead, but so was the 
whole decade. Thus, for the last couple of years, we seem to have been living 
in the '90s -- or so you would believe if you keep up with the popular press. 
</P>
<P>
Any new performer, politician, or "personality" who comes along is referred to 
as "the (pick your noun) of the '90s." No matter that we're not there yet. The 
most obvious example is Arsenio Hall, who has been called "the talk-show host 
of the '90s" so many times that he would have every right to dread the stroke 
of midnight this New Year's Eve. Having been credited with conquering the '90s 
before the decade is even a day old, Hall has nothing to gain and everything to 
lose when the first day of 1990 actually rolls around. 
</P>
<P>
The same with the Oakland A's ("the baseball team of the '90s"), Michelle 
Pfeiffer ("the actress of the '90s"), Infiniti ("the car of the '90s") and all 
of the other people, places and things who have, before the fact, been chosen 
to epitomize the decade. They are all part of an era that has become so 
impatient with today that tomorrow must be willed into existence well in 
advance. 
</P>
<P>
Save your true compassion, though, for the '90s itself. Thinking of the decade 
once more as a person, the poor, puzzled fellow is going to arrive right on 
schedule -- only to be greeted by a nation that will gaze upon him and think, 
"You again?" The '90s have been with us in spirit for so many months now that 
when the decade actually shows up, much of the country will be bored with it 
without knowing precisely why. 
</P>
<P>
But back to the magazine editor from Manhattan, and her request for a name for 
the '90s. She did not seem interested in hearing reasons why it makes no sense 
to name a decade before the decade starts; she seemed interested in getting a 
name for it. Just doing her job. 
</P>
<P>
"All right," I said. "The '90s is the last decade of the century, right?" 
</P>
<P>
"That's right," she said. 
</P>
<P>
"Then how about something along the lines of 'Get Us Out of Here'?" I said. 
</P>
<P>
"The 'Get Us Out of Here Decade'?" she said. 
</P>
<P>
"It's just a thought," I said. Happy New Year, everybody. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
