</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dexter Manley, former Washington Redskins defensive end, probably will not 
appeal his drug-related lifetime suspension by the NFL in court, his attorney 
said. 
</P>
<P>
Manley, 30, was banished from the league last week for a third violation of the 
NFL's drug abuse policy. There was speculation that Manley would fight the 
suspension in court, either by claiming that the drug test was faulty or by 
questioning the authority of the commissioner or the rule itself. 
</P>
<P>
Manley instead is leaning toward complying with the suspension and seeking 
reinstatement in one year, a provision of the league's policy. 
</P>
<P>
"I know that he has never really indicated to me that he was thinking in terms 
of taking the league to court," said Bob Woolf, Manley's attorney. 
