<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: COUPLE'S BODIES FOUND AT BASE OF SAN PEDRO 
CLIFF 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A man and a woman fell or jumped to their deaths from a rocky 150-foot cliff 
overlooking the Pacific Ocean in Point Fermin Park in San Pedro, police said 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles Police Sgt. Jerry Rilling said investigators believe the couple 
probably jumped because they had to deliberately climb over a fence to get to 
the edge of the cliff. 
</P>
<P>
The bodies, discovered shortly before noon in rocks at the base of the cliff, 
were airlifted by helicopter several hours later and examined nearby. 
</P>
<P>
Rilling said the man carried out-of-date identification with an address in 
Hawthorne and the woman carried no identification. The man was in his early 40s 
and the woman in her late 30s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
